# not-in-image — why each upstream-only patch is absent from the MiSTer image.
#
# scripts/export-kernel-tree.sh publishes these reasons as a table in the generated
# EXPORT.md, so upstream reviewers can see which patches this tree carries that the
# MiSTer image does not, and why. The export FAILS CLOSED if a patch in this directory
# has no reason in either place it looks:
#
#   1. a `Not-in-image: <reason>` line in the patch's own commit message  (preferred --
#      it travels with the patch through rebases and re-exports);
#   2. a row in THIS file  (for patches imported verbatim from the fork, where editing
#      the commit message would mean rewriting someone else's commit text).
#
# Format:  <patch filename><whitespace><one-line reason>
#   Blank lines and lines beginning with '#' are ignored. The reason is rendered into a
#   markdown table cell, so keep it to one line and prose rather than layout.
#
# A row here for a patch that no longer exists is simply unused; a patch with no row and
# no `Not-in-image:` line stops the export.
#
# There are deliberately NO rows right now. 0100-init-support-for-init-loop-device.patch
# carries its reason as a `Not-in-image:` trailer in its own commit message, which takes
# precedence over this file. Carrying it in both places meant two separately-worded
# reasons for one patch, and the losing copy could drift for months without anyone
# noticing -- until a precedence change silently altered the text published to upstream in
# EXPORT.md. This file stays for the case it is actually for: a patch imported verbatim
# from the fork, where adding a trailer would mean rewriting someone else's commit text.
